snippet.textDisplay:
Dude, I've been doing this since 2011. I've had a dual socket X5690 running a triple seat gaming capable workstation since back then. I only just upgraded it to an Epyc 7402.
Not impressed by that motherboard, the bottom 8 memory sockets block the top 4 PCIe slots from containing a full length card. Asrock EPYCD8 is a much better choice. It's only PCIe v3, but you'll never notice the difference on any of the workloads you mentioned.
If you wanted to share a single GPU, a reasonably decent Quadro would have probably cost a comparable amount on ebay to a 2080Ti + 2x 2070.
Finally - you could have just used USB 3 active repeater cables. You never would have been able to tell the difference.
snippet.textOriginal:
Dude, I've been doing this since 2011. I've had a dual socket X5690 running a triple seat gaming capable workstation since back then. I only just upgraded it to an Epyc 7402.
Not impressed by that motherboard, the bottom 8 memory sockets block the top 4 PCIe slots from containing a full length card. Asrock EPYCD8 is a much better choice. It's only PCIe v3, but you'll never notice the difference on any of the workloads you mentioned.
If you wanted to share a single GPU, a reasonably decent Quadro would have probably cost a comparable amount on ebay to a 2080Ti + 2x 2070.
Finally - you could have just used USB 3 active repeater cables. You never would have been able to tell the difference.

snippet.textDisplay:
Dude. Don't use a USB flash drive for your OS. That's not even close to an appropriate use case. It's gonna die in 1-2 years, and then you're gonna have a really bad day.
Get a proper SSD in there.

And yeah, he did that cable pull wrong. Honestly? For this sort of setup you'd probably want to install a conduit. It simplifies future pulls, which you in particular are likely to do, and it provides a measure of protection from your known problem of squirrels.
